input_size = 784
output_size = 10
hidden_size = 1024

epochs = 35
batch_size = 400
learning_rate = 0.008
In [6]:
class NeuralNet(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size, output_size, hidden_size):
        super(NeuralNet, self).__init__()
        self.input_layer = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_size)
        self.hidden_layer1 = nn.Linear(hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.hidden_layer2 = nn.Linear(hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.hidden_layer3 = nn.Linear(hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.hidden_layer4 = nn.Linear(hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.hidden_layer5 = nn.Linear(hidden_size, hidden_size)
        self.output_layer = nn.Linear(hidden_size, output_size)
        self.activation = nn.ReLU()

    def forward(self, data):
        self.data = data
        self.output_input_layer = self.activation(
            self.input_layer(self.data)
        )
        self.output_1st_hidden = self.activation(
            self.hidden_layer1(self.output_input_layer)
        )
        self.output_2nd_hidden = self.activation(
            self.hidden_layer2(self.output_1st_hidden)
        )
        self.output_3rd_hidden = self.activation(
            self.hidden_layer3(self.output_2nd_hidden)
        )
        self.output_4th_hidden = self.activation(
            self.hidden_layer4(self.output_3rd_hidden)
        )
        self.output_5th_hidden = self.activation(
            self.hidden_layer5(self.output_4th_hidden)
        )
        self.final_output = self.output_layer(self.output_5th_hidden)

        self.softmax_output = F.log_softmax(self.final_output, dim = 1)

        
        
        return self.final_output

Training¶

In [7]:
net = NeuralNet(input_size, output_size, hidden_size).cuda()

loss_function = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

# optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(net.parameters(), lr = learning_rate)
optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(net.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, momentum=0.9)

loss_log = []

for e in range(epochs):
    for i in range(0, 60000, batch_size):
        x_mini = x_train[i:i + batch_size] 
        y_mini = y_train[i:i + batch_size] 

        optimizer.zero_grad()
        net_out = net(x_mini.cuda())
        
        loss = loss_function(net_out, y_mini.cuda())
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        
    loss_log.append(loss.data)
    print('Epoch: {} - Loss: {:.6f}'.format(e, loss.data))
    
    
plt.plot(list(range(epochs)),loss_log)

Testing

correct = 0
with torch.no_grad():
    outputs = net(x_test.cuda())
    _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
    correct = sum(predicted.cpu().numpy()== y_test.numpy())
print("Accuracy", (correct/len(y_test))*100)

Each node in the hidden layer represent some template/feature eg. straight lines/ curves and all images that contains the feature(that the hidden node represents) activates the node. There can also be nodes which are not so popular and tries to capture some feature/template not present in any of the images - which leads to empty/incomplete rows. Ideal scenario would have been each of the rows had images belonging to the same class, but since certain features are common to images belonging to different classes we see the matrix as above.¶

PCA & t-SNE

In [11]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE

pca = PCA(n_components = 2)
tsne = TSNE(n_components = 2)

def plot_scatter(technique, x, y):
  colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'purple', 'yellow',
          'black','orange','brown','grey','navy']

  n_samples = len(y)
  # applying pca/tsne to n_samples
  x_technique = technique.fit_transform(x)

#   print(x_technique.shape, y.reshape(n_samples,1).shape )
  x_technique_w_y = np.hstack((x_technique, y.reshape(n_samples,1)))
  
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))

  for i in range(10):
    x_technique_temp = x_technique_w_y[x_technique_w_y[:, 2] == i,]
    
    plt.scatter(x_technique_temp[:, 0], 
                x_technique_temp[:, 1], 
                c = colors[i],
                s = 10)
    plt.text(np.mean(x_technique_temp[:, 0]), 
             np.mean(x_technique_temp[:, 1]),
             i, 
             fontsize = 15)
    
  plt.legend(list(range(10)))
  plt.grid()
  plt.title(technique)
  plt.xlabel('First component')
  plt.ylabel('Second component')

  
plot_scatter(pca, x_test[:1000], y_test[:1000])
plot_scatter(tsne, x_test[:1000], y_test[:1000])

As we can see when we look at projection of the images of 10 class it is no longer easy to classify them using simple decision boundaries as their is a lot of overlap between images of different classes

Last Layer Output(Final_Layer)¶

In [17]:

As we continue through the hidden layers till the output layer we can see that the separation becomes better as we go deep into the network. Once interesting thing to observe is t-sne gives better representation in 2d space as compared to PCA. This is probably because the 2 components in PCA is not enough to capture the variance between the 10 classes
